04292nam a22005775i 9780889205543DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892055437 a10.51644/97808892055432doi  a(DE-B1597)667947  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD810.C36bC39 2003eb 7aBIO0080002bisacsh04a940.54/78/0921 aWilmot, Laurence F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThrough the Hitler Line :bMemoirs of an Infantry Chaplain /cLaurence F. Wilmot. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife Writing00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Photographs -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tTreading Cautiously into the Unknown -- tMinistry on the Arielli Front -- tTaking Up God’s Armour -- tBreaking the Hitler Line -- tA Tourist in Wartime -- tPreparing for the Attack -- tTragedy at Foglia River -- tFierce Fighting and Close Calls -- tA Time of Stress and a Moment of Rest -- tRoman Holiday, Russi Road -- tPrayers for the Fallen -- tLiberating Holland -- tThe Guns Fall Silent -- tGlossary -- tLife Writing Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLaurence Wilmot’s Second World War memoir is a rare thing: a first-hand account of front-line battle by an army officer who is a resolute non-combatant. And it is paradoxes such as this that also make Wilmot’s book a unique and compelling document. Wilmot, as an Anglican chaplain, is a priest dressed as a warrior, a man of peace in battle fatigues. He is an incongruous figure in a theatre of war, always vigilant for opportunities to partake of silent meditation and prayer, never failing to lose sight of the larger moral issues of the war. His compassion is boundless, his sensitivity acute, and one senses his mounting emotional and spiritual enervation as the death toll of his fellow serving men steadily mounts. At the centre of the book is Wilmot’s witness of the murderous battle at the Arielli. Wilmot’s compassion for the fighting men compels him to leave the safety of his ministry and join them at the front, at great personal risk. There, as an unarmed stretcher-bearer, he is kept busy transporting the wounded under enemy fire. In this crucible of battle we see the qualities that attest to Wilmot’s character and contribute to his memoir’s importance: an indefatigable devotion to his duty to save and comfort the wounded, and a resolve to resist despair in spite of the terrible carnage all around. In short, a singular triumph of the decency of one man in the midst of total war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary chaplainsxBiographyxCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCampaignsxItaly. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 4aLife Writing. 4aReligion. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Military.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920554340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889205543423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889205543/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles